    {
      "text": "Which of the following is contraindicated in patients with acute intermittent porphyria?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Thiopentone"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Propofol"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Etomidate"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Ketamine"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: A) Thiopentone</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Thiopentone</strong> is contraindicated in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8502a8f15e16927771909160b28bf2\">intermittent</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e5f770f89c16927771966b9e3da618\">porphyria</span> (AIP). AIP is a disorder of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d4fff554a316927771885dc8700abe\">heme</span> biosynthesis, and thiopentone, a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8815b1ff5b1692777182be93e820b0\">barbiturate</span> used for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f447020b9616927771904d1c923d80\">induction</span> of anesthesia, can trigger an <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> attack of porphyria. It induces the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3fda45538a1692777199ec2a5478a5\">synthesis</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4a759c9f1016927771964b8325ac2f\">porphyrin</span> precursors, exacerbating the disease and leading to symptoms such as <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1665a40f1016927771801899eaed5d\">abdominal</span> pain, neuropathy, and mental changes.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Incorrect Options:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Propofol (option B)</strong> is considered safe for use in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8502a8f15e16927771909160b28bf2\">intermittent</span> porphyria. It does not induce the production of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4a759c9f1016927771964b8325ac2f\">porphyrin</span> precursors and is a commonly used <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4b83ec31581692777181547f1a89ef\">anesthetic</span> agent in these patients.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Etomidate (option C)</strong> is another <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4b83ec31581692777181547f1a89ef\">anesthetic</span> agent that is generally safe for use in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8502a8f15e16927771909160b28bf2\">intermittent</span> porphyria. It does not affect the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d4fff554a316927771885dc8700abe\">heme</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3aa5abc2fa169277719488e088076d\">pathway</span> and is often preferred in situations where other agents might be contraindicated.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Ketamine (option D)</strong> can be used in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4cdc8161f71692777180df58cafa93\">acute</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8502a8f15e16927771909160b28bf2\">intermittent</span> porphyria. It does not interfere with the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4a759c9f1016927771964b8325ac2f\">porphyrin</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"859a34e1061692777183872a5e4441\">biosynthesis</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3aa5abc2fa169277719488e088076d\">pathway</span> and is often used in situations where general <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e24b7bd55d16927771818aaa6ad0ed\">anesthesia</span> is required, especially in cases of trauma or when other agents are contraindicated.</p>",
